Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). When hot, add the
@lamb mince{200%g} and fry, breaking it up with a #wooden spoon{}, until
browned, ~{3-4%mins}. Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%can} in a
#sieve{}.

When the lamb has browned, stir in the @Malay curry powder{2%tsp} (careful, it's
hot!) and cook for ~{30%seconds}. Stir in the chickpeas, @chicken stock powder{1%tsp},
@tomato passata{1%jar}, @water{100%ml} and a @?sugar{pinch}.

Stir everything together then bring to the boil, reduce the heat and simmer until
thick and tomatoey, stirring occasionally ~{8-10%mins}. IMPORTANT: The lamb is
cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

While the curry cooks, heat another frying pan on high heat. When hot, add a
@super soft tortilla{1} and leave until charred on one side, about ~{30%seconds}.
Turn and cook on the other side, then transfer to a #plate{} and cover with
#foil{} to keep warm while you cook the remaining @super soft tortillas{3}.

> These are your cheat's chapatis!

When the curry is nice and thick, stir the @baby spinach{125%g} in a handful at a
time to wilt it. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}. TIP: Add a splash of
water if it looks a little dry.

Serve the Malay lamb curry in #bowls{} with the cheat's chapatis on the side for
scooping. Enjoy!